dies will find a vivid exploration of how female roles and feminine identity have evolved over 350 years, from the Tokugawa era to the end of World War II. Starting from the premise that gender is not a biological given, but is socially constructed and culturally transmitted, the authors describe the forces of change in the construction of female gender and explore the gap between the ideal of womanhood and the reality of Japanese women's lives. Most of all, the contributors speak to the diversity that has characterized women's experience in Japan. This is an imaginative, pioneering work, offering an interdisciplinary approach that will encourage a reconsideration of the paradigms of women's history, hitherto rooted in the Western experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFeminismzJapanxHistory. 0aWomenxEmploymentzJapanxHistory. 0aWomenzJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aagriculture.  aartisan.  abakufu.  aclass.  adivision of labor.  adomesticity.  afemininity.  afeminism.  agender hierarchy.  agender roles.  agender studies.  agender.  agendered labor.  ahandicrafts.  ahousehold chores.  ahousehold labor.  ajapan.  ajapanese women.  ameiji restoration.  amerchants.  amisogyny.  aonnagata.  aonnarashisa.  aotokorashisa.  apatriarchy.  apeasants.  apost war.  apreindustrial society.  asamurai.  asexuality.  ashingaku.  astatus.  atokugawa.  awealth.  awomanhood.  awomen and labor.  awomen in history.  awomen in the workforce.  awomens studies.  awomens work.  aworking women.1 aBernstein, Gail Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Gail Lee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCaplan, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab